results.notes:
I believe this is P. Cinctulus for many reasons:
1. Cinnamon patch at center of cap
2. Brown band followed by lighter band at edge of cap
3. The water soaked specimens were blackened significantly
4. Grey/black mottled gills with a black spore print. Older specimens gills are black
5. A slight silver lining on the gill edges
6. 3 intermediate tiers of gills between the stem-to-edge gills
7. Found growing on horse manure and used hay overtaken by grass
8. Medium sized mushroom, 2-3 inch cap at full growth
9. Young specimens are hemispherical, older specimens becoming flat
10. Very old specimens caps are flaring upwards revealing rounded gills when viewed edge on
11. Hollow Stem
12. Very slight knob remaining in older specimens. Some more pronounced than others.
Please leave a comment if you agree or disagree, and also what you suggest i do next for identification.

Psathyrella sp.
05/23/2020
Lake Maria State Park, Monticello, MN (Wright County)

- Habitat: Big woods remnant with glacially impacted terrain.
-Habit: 3 – 4 growing individually in small area
- Substrate: Dead oak.
- Associated taxa: Peziza sp. found nearby
- Cap: KOH (5%) nagative to brownish after 60 seconds. 15-20mm width. Lighter at edge and fading fast after harvesting). Light brown with tinges of yellow/honey. Bald. Convex with hint of umbo. Noticable striations.
- Gills: Attached to stem. Close. A darker shade of brownish/purple than cap. 5-8mm length (3mm height).
- Stem: More or less equal. No visible ring. Tan-to-light brown. Stuffed. Becoming dingy yellow-tinged brown at base. Fragile (split easy). Length: 15-25mm (2-5mm width)
- Microscopic features: Smooth cylindrical spores. Bowling pin shaped cheilocystidia. 2-3? prong basidia noticed.
- Spore print: Black

notes_fields.Macro: This solitary mushroom was discovered in a grassy cattle pasture growing from dung. There were no trees nearby. The gills were free and at the time of collection, the cap was melting into a gooey jet-black ink. The stipe was 22.8cm tall with a width at the base (near the ground) of 1.1cm. The stipe tapered uniformly (became less wide) from the base to the cap. The stem was hollow and white inside and out. There was a thin string-like growth dangling inside the hollow stem. The odor was mild and no color change was detected from bruising nor the application of KOH, NH4OH, or FeSo4.
notes_fields.Micro: The only spores collected were from a smear of the ink onto a slide (no staining). Some of the spores could have been immature. The sizes of those that were measured were larger than expected (around 16µm x 9µm) for this species based on the literature I had at hand.

results.notes:
Registros realizados el 21 de octubre de 2021.

Macrocybe titans, Estípite/pie de 36cm de altura y 11 cm de diámetro en la base bulbosa, que se adhiere a la de otros basidiomas, al realizar cortes longitudinales y transversales se observa el contexto homogéneo, compacto y de color blanco, a diferencia del píleo/sombrero, este se caracteriza por ser fibroso, (Central, ligeramente excéntrico, cilíndrico, superficie escuamulosa: escamas recurvadas hacia arriba).

Píleo de 22cm diámetro, convexo a plano, cóncavo en el centro, cutícula glabra, seca, opaca, azonada, en ocasiones finamente escuamulosa y con el margen enrollado. Lamelas (Sinuadas a adnadas, apretadas, borde levemente dentado y con margen el entero). Esporada de color crema. Su hábito de crecimiento puede ser solitario, gregario o en racimos, principalmente sobre el suelo desprovisto de material vegetal. Olor y sabor agradable. Es importante señalar su implementación en proyectos de bioprospección, principalmente en la industria alimentaria.

Recomendaciones para tus registros. Las fotografías y descripciones que hagas, te van a permitir identificar el ejemplar:

-Tomar fotografías de las diferentes estructuras del basidioma/ascoma/cuerpo fructifero/carpoforo/seta (por encima, por debajo y de perfil), su estipe, pileo y base, en el caso de retirar el ejemplar sin conocerlo, debes comprometerte a realizar una descripción detallada para aportar a su conocimiento y que no quede en una muestra arrancada, fotografiada y desechada. Además de retirarlo con sustrato para conocer otras características de la base del basidioma.

-Es importante que describas las dimensiones (altura y diametro), forma, consistencia, textura, color y olor. Recuerda que los ejemplares cambian bastante según su estado de desarrollo, así que es ideal familiarizarse con la zona y temporada en la que crecen, para hacer un seguimiento y logres observar la variabilidad fenotípica del basidioma o ascoma (cuerpo fructífero).

-Toma fotos del entorno y agrega datos del ecosistema (humedad, temperatura, altura, tipo de bosque, insectos asociados, etc).

-No olvides que la determinación de macromicetos es compleja y no se realiza únicamente con fotografías, esta tarea (a nivel de género y especie; en la mayoría) implica actividades de descripción morfológica externa e interna, esporada, reacciones químicas, microscopia e incluso herramientas moleculares (ADN/PCR).
